<section>
    <h1>The <%= Settings.event_name %> CfP process</h1>

    <section id="rationale">
        <h2>Rationale</h2>
        <p>
            The CfP was designed with the following goals in mind:
        </p>

        <ul>
            <li>Encourage proposal submissions by everyone (irrespective of publicity, gender, race, domain etc).</li>
            <li>Encourage refinements on proposals.</li>
            <li>Make sure that the selection process is neutral and unbiased.</li>
            <li>Make sure that the most interesting proposals are actually selected by the community.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <section id="process-overview">
        <h2>The process overview</h2>
        <p>
            The process is an amalgamation of
            <a href="http://vestibule.rubymanor.org/the-vestibule-process" target="_blank">Ruby Manor's ‘Vestibule’ process</a>,
            <a href="https://github.com/euruko2012/call-for-proposals" target="_blank">last year’s EuRuKo</a>
            and our own ideas and favourite picks from various conferences we have attended ourselves in the past.

            The main ideas are rather simple:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>Make it safe and easy for everyone to submit their proposal.</li>
            <li>Gather, discuss and refine a lot of ideas in an anonymous (blind) way without prejudice.</li>
            <li>Make a shortlist of the best proposals using some “interestingness” criteria.</li>
            <li>Publicly vote for the presentations that you want to see.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Phase 1: Submission and discussion</h3>
        <p>
            During Phase 1 the CfP platform will be open to submissions by everyone.
            Authors may submit an unlimited number of proposals.
            During this period everyone will be able to interact with the submitted proposals.
            This means that anyone can:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>Discuss</li>
            <li>Promote/Demote</li>
            <li>Share on social media</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
            Authors may therefore:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>Refine their proposals</li>
            <li>Withdraw their proposals</li>
            <li>Add more proposals</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
            <strong>During this phase, all proposals will appear anonymised to the public.</strong>
            Author names as well as any other information that may give away the identity of the author
            will be redacted at this phase. The rationale is that at this point the audience should be focusing
            on the content rather than the author.
        </p>
        <p>
            With this 'blind' submission, we want to encourage <strong>everyone</strong> to participate
            in <%= Settings.event_name %> and have the chance to have their proposal discussed online
            without prejudice.
        </p>

        <h3>Interlude: Submissions freeze &amp; final call for shortlist selection</h3>
        <p>
            Following the end of Phase 1 <em>(see below for exact dates)</em>, the platform will close for further submissions.
            Consequently the audience may interact with the proposals only for the purpose of making a final shortlist.
            This shortlist will be the one used for the final voting. "Interacting" during this phase means:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>Promote/Demote</li>
            <li>Share on social media</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Authors at this stage may only:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Withdraw</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Phase 2: Final voting &amp; selection</h3>
        <p>
            During phase 2 the audience will be called to vote on the proposals that have at this point
            made it into the shortlist. At this phase <strong>all proposals will be named and the authors
            will be identified, including the ones that didn't make it to the shortlist</strong>.
        </p>
    </section>

